node.text: Bern, the capital of Switzerland is build around a crook in the Azare River. The city was founded in 1191 by Duke Berchtold V of Zähringen. It is said that he exclaimed the new city would be named after the first animal to be found on a hunting expedition in the woods and that animal just so happened to be a bear. The street signs of the Old Town are different colours - green, white, yellow and burgundy. This detail remains from when Napoleon conquered the city in 1798. Santander is a large port city in the north of Spain and is the capital of the Cantabria region. The city dates back to Roman times when it was called Portus Victoriae however the current name is reputed to have its origins in the third century. Located in the heart of London's Hyde Park, Winter Wonderland is touted as the spectacular Christmas destination in London. Hosting over 100 rides and attractions, shows and London's biggest Christmas market, the annual event is sure to bring lots of festive cheer to even the biggest Christmas Grinches! Almeria in the southeast of Spain is infamously known as the greenhouse of Europe. The area uses intensive agriculture methods to produce significant amounts of fruit and vegetables that supply the domestic and European markets. Because of its size, climate and existing infrastructure, this plastic sea has become a hotbed of agricultural and climate science research. The area is constantly under debate as to whether the economic benefit it creates is comparable to the potential impact on the climate, what are your thoughts? Today is Human Rights Day, the day that the UN General Assembly adopted, in 1948, the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. This year marks the 70th anniversary of this major milestone document that proclaimed the inalienable rights of which everyone is inherently entitled to as a human being. This image details a transit camp in Libya of which displaced populations have been forced to reside in due to their human rights being violated within their country. Glaciers blanket more  than a tenth of the entire island, river systems snake through all regions and there are over 10,000 waterfalls throughout the country. Captured with WorldView-2. Can you guess which famous cathedral this is? Let us test your geospatial knowledge. To help you, we will give you some clues. This cathedral is a national monument of France and has been a basilica minor since 1896. It was built over 40 years and was the only cathedral built in France in the 19th century. It is also one of the largest cathedrals in the world! Today marks 30 years since the Berlin Wall fell, ending the German separation and starting a series of events that ultimately led to German reunification and the fall of Communism in Eastern Europe.  The wall was almost 166km long and stood for 28 years before coming down in 1989 to allow free travel within Berlin. Happy Halloween! Who doesn’t' love a haunted house and all things spooky on this ominous day? This image is of Zvikov Castle, one of the most important castles in the Czech Republic. The castle has its own ghost - Zvikov's imp - who has inspired many writers and painters. Fire hounds are also said to guard an underground tunnel, and visitors frequently report technical issues, weird photos and ghosts among other spooky and strange events. The small island is reachable by plane from the mainland and is home to Anantara Kihavah Maldives Villas - a luxury retreat featuring 80 spacious private pool villas along the private beach or poised over the water with private plunge pools allowing guests to dive straight from their rooms into the crystal clear water below. Open pit mining is a surface mining technique and is used when deposits of minerals or rock are found near the surface; that is, where the overburden (surface material) is relatively thin or the area is structurally unsuitable for tunneling (e.g. sand, cinder, and gravel). Satellite Imagery is useful in mining as the different bands can penetrate the surface to identify materials beneath enabling the miner to know exactly what to look for. Today is @unisdr International Day for Disaster Reduction, a day to celebrate how people and communities around the world are reducing their exposure to disaster. Did you know that VHR satellite imagery can be instrumental in reducing natural and man-made disasters and also is a critical tool for first response and crisis management when disaster strikes? Planning equals prevention. With satellite imagery it is possible to predict the likelihood of fires and the paths of floods in addition to detecting geological movements that can be an indicator of possible landslides. Smart planning starts with good data! On this day, 30 years ago, after the weekly prayer for peace in the Nikolaikirche, some 70,000 people moved around the center. "Now or never, democracy," they shouted. Others chanted "Gorbi!", the Russian leader at the time, in hopes he would hear their cries to tear down the wall.  Others sang the famous line "We are the people". Historians see this demonstration as the crucial turning point of the GDR citizens' way to freedom and the tearing down of the Berlin Wall. The demonstration along the city ring sent a signal: This country is changing now.  Those who were there to witnesses this monumental occasion argue whether the Wall would have fallen if it were not for this peaceful revolution. High Atlas, also known as the Grand Atlas is the highest peak of the Atlas Mountains range in central Morocco. It runs diagonally across Morocco for almost 1000 km and contains some of the countries most intriguing and beautiful regions, popular among hikers and mountaineers alike. Tobruk is a port city on Libya's eastern Mediterranean coast near the border of Egypt. It is the capital of the Butnan District and was the site of an ancient Greek colony and later of a Roman fortress. Tobruk is perhaps most famous for the "Siege of Tobruk", a battle during World War 2 that lasted 241 days.
